in Gameloft's portfolio.

64
00:03:15,673 --> 00:03:18,215
Now as a lot of my fellow UX designers would agree,

65
00:03:18,595 --> 00:03:20,677
sometimes when we are moved around projects,

66
00:03:21,097 --> 00:03:22,758
we inherit suboptimal designs.

67
00:03:24,220 --> 00:03:25,501
What exactly do I mean by that?

68
00:03:27,382 --> 00:03:28,523
Any game designers in the house?

69
00:03:32,026 --> 00:03:33,407
So with all due respect guys,

70
00:03:33,467 --> 00:03:35,188
sometimes the systems you design,

71
00:03:35,468 --> 00:03:36,349
though they are functional,

72
00:03:36,469 --> 00:03:39,231
they're not the best example of usability and intuitiveness.

73
00:03:40,092 --> 00:03:41,533
One such system which I inherited

74
00:03:41,713 --> 00:03:43,374
when I was moved on to the Ice Age team

75
00:03:43,775 --> 00:03:45,156
was the existing Even system.

76
00:03:46,193 --> 00:03:47,355
Let me give you a bit more context.

77
00:03:47,475 --> 00:03:50,358
When a game is newly launched, it generates a lot of engagement.

78
00:03:51,439 --> 00:03:53,821
But the fact is, the longer the game stays live,

79
00:03:54,062 --> 00:03:55,763
its novelty value starts wearing off,

80
00:03:56,304 --> 00:03:59,187
and the players start getting bored of the same grinding mechanics.

81
00:04:00,068 --> 00:04:02,470
So, in order to refresh the user experience,

82
00:04:02,830 --> 00:04:05,033
as developers, we have to keep adding new features.

83
00:04:05,753 --> 00:04:07,515
And that is where the Event System comes in.

84
00:04:08,992 --> 00:04:10,693
By looking at usage data, we found that

85
00:04:10,793 --> 00:04:12,954
while the average session time was around 18 minutes,

86
00:04:13,294 --> 00:04:15,215
which is not bad by industry standards,

87
00:04:15,395 --> 00:04:17,636
for those players who took part in the event system,

88
00:04:18,057 --> 00:04:20,038
this average went up to 30, 35 minutes,

89
00:04:20,458 --> 00:04:21,879
practically double of what we were seeing.

90
00:04:22,739 --> 00:04:23,460
And it is well known,

91
00:04:23,640 --> 00:04:25,381
if you can have players spend quality time

92
00:04:25,701 --> 00:04:28,142
and effort in your game, it's much easier to monetize them.

93
00:04:28,923 --> 00:04:30,163
So the event system was designed

94
00:04:30,203 --> 00:04:32,104
to increase the average session length,

95
00:04:32,265 --> 00:04:34,746
which could then have a positive impact on our monetization.

96
00:04:36,027 --> 00:04:36,567
So far, so good.

97
00:04:37,678 --> 00:04:38,880
But here was the problem.

98
00:04:40,642 --> 00:04:45,208
Nowadays when we launch a feature, most companies, there's something called a launch KPI.

99
00:04:45,609 --> 00:04:48,172
It's pretty much like what NASA does with its projects, right?

100
00:04:49,154 --> 00:04:53,139
Based on those launch KPIs, you determine whether a feature launch is successful or

101
00:04:53,219 --> 00:04:53,520
failure.

102
00:04:54,318 --> 00:05:00,182
Now the projected KPI for this game was, sorry, for this feature was 45% participation rate

103
00:05:00,342 --> 00:05:01,462
of existing player base.

104
00:05:02,023 --> 00:05:07,006
However, the ground reality was only 20% of the players converted, which was of course

105
00:05:07,146 --> 00:05:07,666
disappointing.

106
00:05:09,467 --> 00:05:13,070
Now even before I start looking at data to understand where does the bottleneck lie,

107
00:05:13,410 --> 00:05:16,112
it's important to start with certain assumptions.

108
00:05:16,972 --> 00:05:18,753
We had to answer two critical questions here.

109
00:05:19,514 --> 00:05:19,694
Why?

110
00:05:20,807 --> 00:05:22,248
Why do we have such poor numbers?

111
00:05:22,989 --> 00:05:24,610
And what is causing this lack of engagement?

112
00:05:25,270 --> 00:05:26,751
Is it the content system of the event?

113
00:05:27,532 --> 00:05:28,452
Is it not appealing enough?

114
00:05:28,753 --> 00:05:30,414
But the content pipeline was designed

115
00:05:30,614 --> 00:05:33,496
based on upcoming Ice Age movies, which was pretty new.

116
00:05:34,176 --> 00:05:36,118
And of course, we were talking to our players constantly

117
00:05:36,158 --> 00:05:37,258
through our community channels,

118
00:05:37,699 --> 00:05:39,900
asking them what kind of characters they would like to see,

119
00:05:40,060 --> 00:05:41,681
what kind of adventures they would like to go.

120
00:05:42,522 --> 00:05:43,983
So we can safely say that was not it,

121
00:05:44,083 --> 00:05:46,304
because we had a lot of active player feedback

122
00:05:46,545 --> 00:05:47,425
on the content design.

123
00:05:48,766 --> 00:05:49,326
Then what was it?

124
00:05:50,143 --> 00:05:51,904
Is it the discovery and usability of the system?

125
00:05:52,805 --> 00:05:54,826
Are players trying to interact with the feature

126
00:05:54,886 --> 00:05:57,247
but it's so hard to use that they are getting frustrated

127
00:05:57,387 --> 00:05:57,948
and just churning?

128
00:05:58,788 --> 00:06:00,929
Or maybe the events are too hard to complete.

129
00:06:01,650 --> 00:06:02,910
So the players might be signing up

130
00:06:03,350 --> 00:06:04,851
but the competition level is so high

131
00:06:05,291 --> 00:06:07,072
they're just not feeling like, you know,

132
00:06:07,192 --> 00:06:08,613
getting through it or getting frustrated.

133
00:06:10,454 --> 00:06:12,415
In order to validate some of these hypotheses

134
00:06:12,675 --> 00:06:15,197
and rule out others, I had to work very closely

135
00:06:15,357 --> 00:06:16,938
with other departments within the company.

136
00:06:17,653 --> 00:06:22,958
For example, data scientists, who are looking at copious amount of player data, cohort analysis,

137
00:06:23,198 --> 00:06:28,002
and so on. Analytics to understand how players are interacting with this feature, where are they

138
00:06:28,022 --> 00:06:32,166
spending time, where are they dropping off. Business performance managers, who design the

139
00:06:32,226 --> 00:06:37,130
soft and hard currency gates of the game. Now, just by looking at how much currencies or resources

140
00:06:37,511 --> 00:06:41,234
players are spending in a feature, you can have a pretty good idea of engagement.

141
00:06:41,655 --> 00:06:44,457
Because the more engaged they are, more resources they're going to sink.

142
00:06:46,030 --> 00:06:47,311
and of course the community managers.

143
00:06:47,971 --> 00:06:50,093
Working with them, we could design special polls

144
00:06:50,133 --> 00:06:52,534
and surveys to gather qualitative subjective data.

145
00:06:53,895 --> 00:06:56,016
Here's an example of the kind of data we were collecting

146
00:06:56,136 --> 00:06:57,317
and how we were analyzing it.

147
00:06:58,277 --> 00:06:59,978
Number of people clicking on the events icon,

148
00:07:00,339 --> 00:07:01,940
number of people hitting the join button,

149
00:07:02,380 --> 00:07:04,361
number of people dropping off from various drill downs,

150
00:07:04,781 --> 00:07:05,722
event completion rate,

151
00:07:05,962 --> 00:07:07,383
and specially designed surveys and polls.

152
00:07:09,099 --> 00:07:13,964
Now just by looking at the analytic funnel, we could see where exactly in the flow the

153
00:07:14,004 --> 00:07:16,327
drop was happening, where the churn was happening.

154
00:07:17,268 --> 00:07:19,251
This of course gives rise to the next natural question.

155
00:07:19,691 --> 00:07:20,893
Why is that churn happening?

156
00:07:21,834 --> 00:07:25,979
Now in order to understand that, we applied a very popular UX methodology which is called

157
00:07:26,079 --> 00:07:27,120
heuristic diagnosis.

158
00:07:28,620 --> 00:07:31,341
Heuristics stands for a set of special cardinal rules

159
00:07:31,561 --> 00:07:33,603
which when applied to a flow help us understand

160
00:07:33,763 --> 00:07:35,964
how usable or intuitive that flow is.

161
00:07:36,604 --> 00:07:37,965
You can find more information about it

162
00:07:38,145 --> 00:07:39,566
on the Nelson Norman Group website.

163
00:07:39,786 --> 00:07:40,467
I would recommend that.

164
00:07:41,487 --> 00:07:43,768
So, let's see what we uncover

165
00:07:43,969 --> 00:07:45,529
when we apply heuristic diagnosis

166
00:07:45,570 --> 00:07:47,371
