Here you are, coming back to the game, you see all the smoke and mirror,

254
00:11:44,013 --> 00:11:44,393
and then...

255
00:11:44,413 --> 00:11:46,373
the final score is zero.

256
00:11:47,574 --> 00:11:48,534
Your rank is in thousands,

257
00:11:49,154 --> 00:11:50,974
and your reward, big, fat none.

258
00:11:51,314 --> 00:11:51,994
You don't deserve it.

259
00:11:53,175 --> 00:11:53,635
Go away.

260
00:11:55,275 --> 00:11:59,216
So, after creating anticipation and raising expectation,

261
00:11:59,536 --> 00:12:00,776
when the player sees the screen,

262
00:12:02,487 --> 00:12:04,348
She's like, what the fuck just happened?

263
00:12:06,549 --> 00:12:09,811
I mean, while she was expecting positive gratification,

264
00:12:10,351 --> 00:12:12,232
and then she sees a screen which is utterly

265
00:12:12,312 --> 00:12:14,233
lacking in any kind of encouragement,

266
00:12:15,013 --> 00:12:16,854
it seems almost like a dirty trick,

267
00:12:17,354 --> 00:12:18,435
almost like a slap in her face.

268
00:12:19,908 --> 00:12:22,249
So, after applying heuristic diagnosis,

269
00:12:22,469 --> 00:12:24,710
here's a list of issues we found out.

270
00:12:24,930 --> 00:12:26,230
Three drill downs and four clicks

271
00:12:26,630 --> 00:12:28,731
to gather all risk and reward information

272
00:12:28,931 --> 00:12:30,871
that player needs for his decision making.

273
00:12:31,492 --> 00:12:32,732
Text walls, which were repeated

274
00:12:32,832 --> 00:12:33,932
throughout all the drill downs,

275
00:12:34,032 --> 00:12:35,093
that's a suboptimal design.

276
00:12:35,673 --> 00:12:37,433
Busy layouts, confusing CTAs,

277
00:12:37,753 --> 00:12:40,394
and event overscreen, which lacks any kind of encouragement.

278
00:12:41,494 --> 00:12:42,255
Yeah, that's a long list.

279
00:12:44,290 --> 00:12:46,632
Now, you saw that how we collected qualitative

280
00:12:46,852 --> 00:12:49,074
and quantitative data, which helped us understand

281
00:12:49,274 --> 00:12:50,755
where exactly the churn is happening.

282
00:12:51,556 --> 00:12:52,817
We applied heuristic diagnosis,

283
00:12:52,837 --> 00:12:54,779
so we know why that churn is happening.

284
00:12:56,020 --> 00:12:57,921
Do you think now I have enough information

285
00:12:58,182 --> 00:12:59,643
to start designing a solution?

286
00:13:01,304 --> 00:13:03,706
Not yet, because even before I can think

287
00:13:03,766 --> 00:13:04,927
of start designing a solution,

288
00:13:05,128 --> 00:13:06,409
there's one more step in between,

289
00:13:07,149 --> 00:13:08,931
and that is getting a stakeholder buy-in.

290
00:13:10,088 --> 00:13:13,011
The stakeholder group can vary in composition from company to company.

291
00:13:13,392 --> 00:13:16,695
It can have your product leads, dev leads, creative directors, and so on.

292
00:13:17,716 --> 00:13:21,519
Now it is important to understand that any update schedule, as in the case of our game,

293
00:13:21,619 --> 00:13:24,282
has been decided upon three to six months in advance.

294
00:13:25,223 --> 00:13:30,307
So if you turn up at the last minute and say, hey, by the way, we have an important UX fix

295
00:13:30,347 --> 00:13:32,449
to push, it's just not going to happen.

296
00:13:32,790 --> 00:13:34,111
Trust me, I can take my word on that.

297
00:13:35,073 --> 00:13:37,854
What we need to do is we need to get a stakeholder buy-in.

298
00:13:38,294 --> 00:13:41,036
So here I am presenting my analysis to the stakeholder group,

299
00:13:41,416 --> 00:13:43,777
which is the product manager and the dev lead in my case,

300
00:13:44,377 --> 00:13:45,778
and the product has a question for me.

301
00:13:46,799 --> 00:13:47,639
Well, this makes sense,

302
00:13:48,279 --> 00:13:51,141
but why do you think it's more important than 50 other improvements

303
00:13:51,281 --> 00:13:52,381
that we already have lined up?

304
00:13:53,182 --> 00:13:54,603
And the devs have their own angle.

305
00:13:55,523 --> 00:13:56,864
Whatever solution you come up with,

306
00:13:57,204 --> 00:13:58,925
will it reuse existing widgets?

307
00:13:59,505 --> 00:14:03,907
Because if the solution involves creating and writing more code,

308
00:14:04,260 --> 00:14:08,044
that can inflate the sprint time, thereby delaying the overall release schedule.

309
00:14:08,484 --> 00:14:09,565
And that's going to be in my head.

310
00:14:10,446 --> 00:14:11,466
I didn't want that, of course.

311
00:14:12,487 --> 00:14:16,611
Now this is where you leverage working very closely with other stakeholders within the

312
00:14:16,631 --> 00:14:16,911
company.

313
00:14:17,719 --> 00:14:25,605
Based on the analysis, the business performance managers projected there would be a 15% drop in revenue if we do not push for this fix.

314
00:14:26,206 --> 00:14:27,266
And this helped turn the tide.

315
00:14:27,787 --> 00:14:30,049
The product saw that this is a strong case for UX revamp.

316
00:14:30,369 --> 00:14:31,750
Yeah, the money really talks.

317
00:14:32,250 --> 00:14:33,491
That got them sorted.

318
00:14:34,192 --> 00:14:39,616
And the devs also understood that it's important, but we have to be very smart and efficient about carrying out any changes.

319
00:14:41,632 --> 00:14:44,053
Now perhaps you can understand why it was important

320
00:14:44,073 --> 00:14:45,094
to get a stakeholder buy-in,

321
00:14:45,654 --> 00:14:48,336
because I'm not free to design just any solution

322
00:14:48,796 --> 00:14:50,337
that might be so expensive to build

323
00:14:50,637 --> 00:14:52,758
that it will never see the light of day.

324
00:14:53,798 --> 00:14:55,679
Instead, the solution I needed to design

325
00:14:55,959 --> 00:14:57,340
had to hit three distinct goals.

326
00:14:58,240 --> 00:15:00,241
Business goals of increasing player participation rate

327
00:15:00,622 --> 00:15:02,803
and boosting ROI, user experience goals

328
00:15:02,883 --> 00:15:04,043
of reducing cognitive load

329
00:15:04,243 --> 00:15:06,525
and making the whole experience feel more rewarding,

330
00:15:07,085 --> 00:15:08,365
and of course, the development goal

331
00:15:08,526 --> 00:15:10,426
of working within strict budget constraints.

332
00:15:12,469 --> 00:15:13,770
So now we have a green light.

333
00:15:14,090 --> 00:15:15,571
The first thing I like to do afterwards

334
00:15:16,692 --> 00:15:17,712
in order to start on a solution

335
00:15:17,912 --> 00:15:19,373
is to look at the root cause of the problem.

336
00:15:20,334 --> 00:15:23,235
Even before I consider wireframes or hierarchy issues,

337
00:15:23,255 --> 00:15:25,617
the first thing I start with is the logic flows.

338
00:15:26,697 --> 00:15:28,318
This is the existing event logic in our game.

339
00:15:28,798 --> 00:15:30,059
Is there a new event available?

340
00:15:30,419 --> 00:15:33,061
If yes, show player a new notification on HUD.

341
00:15:33,561 --> 00:15:35,762
If player signs up, maintain the new notification.

342
00:15:36,603 --> 00:15:39,284
If not, just show him the remaining time.

343
00:15:40,425 --> 00:15:40,545
Now...

344
00:15:41,214 --> 00:15:43,415
You may well recall when we were applying heuristic diagnosis,

345
00:15:43,555 --> 00:15:46,397
I did point out for a game like ours, which has been live for long,

346
00:15:47,198 --> 00:15:50,640
anytime the player comes back to the game, he has five to six notifications

347
00:15:50,880 --> 00:15:54,042
waiting for his attention. And we deduced it is possible

348
00:15:54,462 --> 00:15:57,665
that this information that a new event is available might be getting drowned.

349
00:15:58,625 --> 00:16:02,268
Or it may be the player is so used to the notification spam, he just treats it

350
00:16:02,328 --> 00:16:06,811
as white noise and blanks it out. Either ways, the discovery of this system

351
00:16:07,091 --> 00:16:10,733
is suffering. So what did we do? We added another step.

352
00:16:11,613 --> 00:16:13,675
trigger an event sign-up UI at launch.

353
00:16:14,275 --> 00:16:16,857
Now, whenever a new event is available,

354
00:16:17,218 --> 00:16:18,339
we trigger a sign-up UI.

355
00:16:18,679 --> 00:16:21,341
What that does is it allows player to sign up for the event

356
00:16:21,582 --> 00:16:23,483
without going through any further drill downs

357
00:16:24,184 --> 00:16:25,105
if he so wishes to.

358
00:16:26,126 --> 00:16:26,806
What did we boost?

359
00:16:27,467 --> 00:16:28,568
We added discovery.

360
00:16:29,909 --> 00:16:31,390
Instead of making player work

361
00:16:31,931 --> 00:16:34,213
to discover a critical piece of information

362
00:16:34,873 --> 00:16:35,994
that you want him to consume,

363
00:16:36,515 --> 00:16:39,017
we have surfaced and brought forth that information for him.

364
00:16:40,584 --> 00:16:43,387
The next flow I looked at was the existing event over logic.

365
00:16:44,048 --> 00:16:46,130
Did player make any progress after signing up?

366
00:16:46,651 --> 00:16:49,814
If yes, display x reward value based on progression.

367
00:16:50,555 --> 00:16:51,756
If not, show a null value.

368
00:16:53,158 --> 00:16:56,121
Now a lot of my programmer friends would say, what's wrong with this logic?

369
00:16:56,601 --> 00:16:57,322
Makes sense, right?

370
00:16:57,542 --> 00:17:00,886
If the player did not make any progress, he would see a null reward value.

371
00:17:02,555 --> 00:17:06,116
But what I would like to argue is while the logic is spot on, from a neuropsychological

372
00:17:06,176 --> 00:17:10,938
point of view, we are dealing with a very casual player base, a lot of teen and tween

373
00:17:11,018 --> 00:17:15,819
players, and when we show them a reward screen, they're expecting positive gratification.

374
00:17:16,860 --> 00:17:17,480
So what did we do?

375
00:17:17,780 --> 00:17:21,361
We added another step, display minimum participation reward.

376
00:17:21,941 --> 00:17:26,542
Now, even if the player does not make any progress after signing up, we still give him

377
00:17:26,742 --> 00:17:27,883
a small participation reward.

378
00:17:29,133 --> 00:17:31,015
What did we change compared to the previous flow?

379
00:17:31,395 --> 00:17:32,456
We added empathy.

380
00:17:33,356 --> 00:17:36,138
What this does is it makes us, the developers, look generous

381
00:17:36,398 --> 00:17:38,540
and shows players there is a positive incentive

382
00:17:38,640 --> 00:17:40,241
in taking part in the event system.

383
00:17:41,702 --> 00:17:43,883
So the two key changes we achieved in our logic flows,

384
00:17:44,283 --> 00:17:47,125
we boosted discovery by triggering a sign-up UI at launch

385
00:17:47,265 --> 00:17:48,446
whenever a new event is available,

386
00:17:48,886 --> 00:17:51,148
and we added empathy by giving players

387
00:17:51,208 --> 00:17:52,448
a minimum participation reward.

388
00:17:53,929 --> 00:17:54,910
The next step was, of course,

389
00:17:54,970 --> 00:17:57,131
to do some whiteboarding sessions, some brainstorming.

390
00:17:58,492 --> 00:18:00,394
along with your game designers, producers,

391
00:18:00,454 --> 00:18:01,735
and all the other parties involved.

392
00:18:02,015 --> 00:18:03,356
We created some rough wireframes.

393
00:18:03,917 --> 00:18:04,938
Once we were happy with those,

394
00:18:05,138 --> 00:18:06,480
we created digital counterparts.

395
00:18:07,240 --> 00:18:09,262
And after we've iterated enough on these,

396
00:18:09,503 --> 00:18:10,944
we created a working prototype.

397
00:18:12,185 --> 00:18:14,467
So let's see, what did we change in the new flow

398
00:18:14,728 --> 00:18:16,550
in order to address all the issues

399
00:18:16,710 --> 00:18:19,052
that we saw during the heuristic diagnosis stage?

400
00:18:20,673 --> 00:18:22,314
Now when the player clicks on the event icon,

401
00:18:22,655 --> 00:18:23,535
he's brought to this view.

402
00:18:23,856 --> 00:18:26,097
You can see that each event is now its own bucket

403
00:18:26,698 --> 00:18:27,659
using a tabular system.

404
00:18:28,099 --> 00:18:29,580
We rearrange the information hierarchy

405
00:18:29,600 --> 00:18:31,442
so it's easier to read from top to bottom

406
00:18:31,522 --> 00:18:32,223
and left to right.

407
00:18:32,983 --> 00:18:36,226
And leaderboards is now a smart slide-in slide-out drawer.

408
00:18:36,666 --> 00:18:39,149
What this does is, this layout allows the player

409
00:18:39,189 --> 00:18:41,751
to gather all the risk and reward information he needs

410
00:18:42,071 --> 00:18:44,693
within the very same view without switch of context

411
00:18:45,174 --> 00:18:47,476
and it reduces the number of drill downs

412
00:18:47,576 --> 00:18:49,117
from three to just one.

413
00:18:50,089 --> 00:18:52,510
So the key changes we achieved in our new flow,

414
00:18:53,010 --> 00:18:54,770
we rearranged information hierarchy

415
00:18:54,790 --> 00:18:55,851
so it's easier to digest,

416
00:18:56,291 --> 00:18:58,572
we reduced drill downs from three to just one click,

417
00:18:59,032 --> 00:19:01,412
leaderboard is now a smart slide-in slide-out drawer,

418
00:19:02,033 --> 00:19:03,453
and we reduced cognitive load

419
00:19:03,593 --> 00:19:06,034
because we got rid of all the drill downs altogether.

420
00:19:07,854 --> 00:19:10,515
So, we have a solution now, which looks pretty good.

421
00:19:10,895 --> 00:19:14,276
The next step, as per UX methodology, is to test it.

422
00:19:16,097 --> 00:19:18,077
Now you would ask, why should we test it?

423
00:19:18,097 --> 00:19:19,758
We have tested it enough among ourselves, right?

424
00:19:21,608 --> 00:19:25,672
I would like to highlight the mindset with which the designers used to work earlier was

425
00:19:25,712 --> 00:19:27,573
about design for people.

426
00:19:28,934 --> 00:19:31,776
And I say I'm not the kind of designer who designs for people.

427
00:19:32,757 --> 00:19:34,198
You might find that controversial, right?

428
00:19:34,879 --> 00:19:36,240
After all UX is all about people.

429
00:19:38,702 --> 00:19:40,683
Let me like expand on it a bit more.

430
00:19:41,844 --> 00:19:44,266
When designers earlier used to say we are designing for people.

431
00:19:45,118 --> 00:19:46,780
They are making all sorts of assumptions.

432
00:19:47,280 --> 00:19:48,601
Yes, this is what the players will like.

433
00:19:48,701 --> 00:19:50,082
Yes, that is what the players would like.

434
00:19:50,402 --> 00:19:52,043
Or they might ask a few people around them,

435
00:19:52,623 --> 00:19:53,884
and that gave them the idea,

436
00:19:53,984 --> 00:19:56,346
OK, design for people, I know what they want.

437
00:19:57,106 --> 00:19:59,488
But still, they're working just on assumptions.

438
00:19:59,908 --> 00:20:05,131
Instead, UX as a methodology promotes for designing with people.

439
00:20:05,472 --> 00:20:09,054
And that is where focus group testing and usability testing come into play.

440
00:20:10,117 --> 00:20:12,517
Now normally you would go for a full-blown usability test,

441
00:20:12,678 --> 00:20:14,958
but since we were pressed for time, we did the next best thing,

442
00:20:15,198 --> 00:20:17,839
and that was a focus group testing session within the company.

443
00:20:18,920 --> 00:20:21,901
Luckily, in a studio like ours, we had three different teams

444
00:20:21,981 --> 00:20:23,241
working on three different projects.

445
00:20:23,602 --> 00:20:25,682
That meant we had a pool of players who did not know

446
00:20:25,722 --> 00:20:27,983
what's happening much in other teams' project.

447
00:20:28,383 --> 00:20:32,065
So we had a perfect pool of players who could give us unbiased reviews.

448
00:20:32,965 --> 00:20:35,906
We tested our prototype with them, we got some positive feedback,

449
00:20:36,306 --> 00:20:38,507
and on basis of that, this solution was greenlighted.

450
00:20:39,500 --> 00:20:43,662
The next step was, of course, to work with the UI designer on this project and the front-end

451
00:20:43,722 --> 00:20:48,463
engineers in order to make sure justice is done to our vision and to solve any UX problems

452
00:20:48,623 --> 00:20:50,484
we may encounter while implementing it.

453
00:20:52,024 --> 00:20:57,406
Happy to say we managed to push this update out on time with this new fix, and we were

454
00:20:57,666 --> 00:21:00,067
all very pleasantly surprised with what happened next.

455
00:21:01,910 --> 00:21:06,215
This new update not only managed to meet the launch KPI of 45%,

456
00:21:06,656 --> 00:21:08,298
but within a small window of time,

457
00:21:08,578 --> 00:21:13,404
we saw the engagement rate go all the way from 20% to 80%,

458
00:21:13,684 --> 00:21:17,889
which was a humongous 300% jump compared to the previous update.

459
00:21:19,471 --> 00:21:20,853
Important thing here to remember is.

460
00:21:21,684 --> 00:21:24,706
without redesigning or rehauling the entire event system

461
00:21:25,366 --> 00:21:27,228
or writing copious amount of new code,

462
00:21:27,868 --> 00:21:29,870
just by applying the correct UX methodology

463
00:21:30,130 --> 00:21:31,811
in not only diagnosing the problem,

464
00:21:32,191 --> 00:21:33,673
but also designing a solution

465
00:21:33,833 --> 00:21:35,354
which resonated with our player base,

466
00:21:35,754 --> 00:21:38,436
we were able to have such a huge impact on our KPIs.

467
00:21:40,097 --> 00:21:41,138
Next, there was a debrief session

468
00:21:41,438 --> 00:21:42,839
and we had some clear-cut takeaways.

469
00:21:43,540 --> 00:21:45,782
Do not create unnecessary choice biases.

470
00:21:46,462 --> 00:21:49,284
Do not overhelm the player with too much information.

471
00:21:49,785 --> 00:21:50,405
Boost discovery.

472
00:21:51,974 --> 00:21:55,796
If there is a critical piece of information you want players to see or interact with,

473
00:21:55,937 --> 00:21:58,478
do not bury it, do not make them work to discover it.

474
00:21:58,718 --> 00:22:00,980
Instead, surface and bring it forth for them.

475
00:22:02,285 --> 00:22:04,606
Show empathy and use reward screens to convert players.

476
00:22:05,247 --> 00:22:07,188
This is interesting because after we added

477
00:22:07,328 --> 00:22:08,889
the minimum participation reward,

478
00:22:09,449 --> 00:22:11,450
we saw that a huge chunk of players

479
00:22:11,510 --> 00:22:12,671
who were just early signing up,

480
00:22:12,951 --> 00:22:14,092
but not making any progress,

481
00:22:14,752 --> 00:22:16,713
saw a positive incentive in taking part

482
00:22:16,853 --> 00:22:18,374
and started interacting with the system.

483
00:22:18,815 --> 00:22:21,136
And this partly led to the huge 300% jump

484
00:22:21,276 --> 00:22:22,317
you saw in the previous slide.

485
00:22:23,597 --> 00:22:25,358
Last but not least, leverage data.

486
00:22:25,859 --> 00:22:28,500
Work very closely with other departments within the company.

487
00:22:29,222 --> 00:22:31,863
Because not only will they help you gather qualitative

488
00:22:31,983 --> 00:22:34,684
and quantitative data to diagnose a issue,

489
00:22:34,984 --> 00:22:37,965
but when the time comes to make a push for the UX fix

490
00:22:38,505 --> 00:22:39,585
in front of the stakeholder group,

491
00:22:39,785 --> 00:22:41,186
they'll be there backing you up,

492
00:22:41,426 --> 00:22:42,986
helping you make a stronger case.

493
00:22:44,547 --> 00:22:45,727
So with that, ladies and gentlemen,

494
00:22:45,907 --> 00:22:47,268
we've come to an end of our presentation.

495
00:22:47,288 --> 00:22:49,069
I hope it was informative.

496
00:22:49,849 --> 00:22:52,150
And the floor is now open for questions, I guess.

497
00:23:00,104 --> 00:23:02,316
In case you have any questions, please come forward to the mic.

498
00:23:11,885 --> 00:23:14,527
Hi, I'm James Berg, researcher with EA.

499
00:23:14,627 --> 00:23:16,368
Great presentation, thank you.

500
00:23:16,608 --> 00:23:18,529
You mentioned for this particular example,

501
00:23:18,930 --> 00:23:20,791
you're under some pretty severe time constraints.

502
00:23:21,271 --> 00:23:23,593
So I'm wondering, what would you approach differently

503
00:23:24,153 --> 00:23:25,775
if you had all the time that you,

504
00:23:25,815 --> 00:23:26,975
well, maybe not all the time you wanted,

505
00:23:27,015 --> 00:23:29,457
but a realistic amount of extra time added?

506
00:23:29,537 --> 00:23:30,458
What would you have done differently

507
00:23:30,558 --> 00:23:32,059
to approach solving the UX problems?

